div.div:
1. Objects with attribute alignment
- parallel direction
- cooperative shapes like angled endpoint paired with non-angled endpoint
- variation at connection points (angled vs. non-angled endpoints)
- a pair of two units makes sense here because a third type would conflate this unit cooperation relationship in this context
2. apply subset process to objects with aligned attributes (parallel pairs) to create a ratio attribute relationship of an attribute (length) between object having aligned attributes (direction, cooperative attributes), and ensure both units in each pair have angled endpoint attribute (to create cascading variation or alignment later), and permute the application of the subset process to the other unit in the pair (so there's a gap adjacent to the target object)
3. distort target object (in a location & with a method that will create a distortion space with gaps that can mimic itself for copying potential) & apply switching process to permute direction of an object endpoint aligning with a distortion or center of the target (bold) objects, so that angled endpoint of invading object aligns with corner attribute of target object distortion/center
4a. (SDSA) extend distortion & alignment to fill gap at bottom of distortion space, aligning generated (dotted) line with former position in distortion space to create new backup replacement boundary to make the original segment unnecessary
4b (DHJ) extend distortion & alignment to fill gap at bottom of distortion space, and raise distorted subset of target object to fill gap in original object.
5a. (SDSA) fill gap created by ratio with backup/replacement/alternative boundary
5b (DHJ) solidify/aggregate/connect subset combinations & connect alternating subsets of adjacent lower original object & higher target object in pairs
6a (SDSA) close gaps between original pair subsets & new boundary subset
6b (DHJ) apply switch process to finish swap of alternating subsets
This can be abstracted to:
- remove pair restriction (converting it to a set)
- change definitions of attributes
- change the attribute values
- change the definition of alignment
- change which attributes are aligned
- change which objects/subsets are switched
- change the definition of subsets
- change which objects are involved
- change the definition of adjacence
- change the resource to switch
- change the processes applied to conduct the switch
- change the core objects involved (angled ends, angle, corner) allowing these processes to work
and other processing to apply this insight path in other contexts, without sacrificing the insights of the path
Insights from insight path:
- a backup/alternative/replacement object should be constructed before removing key resources like instructions/information
- simple core processes & objects are necessary to conduct a complex operation like an instruction swap with far-reaching consequences
- there are many ways to conduct a complex operation
- some attributes need to have similarities (alignment, cooperation) in order for a similarity-based operation (copying, switching subsets) to be executed
- some object attributes need to exist in order for a swap operation to be valid, such as a multiple sets of similar or equal objects, and adjacence, and core objects like angles & corners
- attributes of core objects can have wide-ranging impact (injection, tearing, alignment between angles/corners)
